snippet.textDisplay: The triple double era vs era thing. Think of back in the early decade of NBA basketball, rebounds were nothing, just common currency, because teams were trigger-happy like crazy. Chamberlain or Thurmond or the best big men could get 25-30 rebounds in a game regularly. Now think of the grind that was the 90s. What just ONE rebound represents. Barkley and Rodman were beasts and could pull down 15+ of those. Today's league is much closer to the early NBA period.

Think of back in the early decade of NBA basketball, rebounds were nothing, just common currency, because teams were trigger-happy like crazy. Chamberlain or Thurmond or the best big men could get 25-30 rebounds in a game regularly. Now think of the grind that was the 90s. What just ONE rebound represents. snippet.textDisplay:
Scoring changed:
The league average points per game have increased +10 in the last 5 years.
Rebounding changed:
Rules like the 14-sec rule after an offensive rebound force more shots, hence more potential rebounds. And also the 3pt era allows for more rebound and further out from the paint (so guards can get more rebounds).
Assists changed:
More ISO ball and the death of mid-range means collapsing defenses and the primary playmaker kicks the ball to the shooter more often. Unlike in the past, where ball movement was spread out to the whole team.
